ce:section.ce:para:
To explore the effect of GQDs concentration on device performance, three PP@GQDs/Lu0.39In0.61O/GaN devices with different volume fraction ratios of GQDs to PEDOT:PSS (VolGQDs/VolPP) are measured. These devices, with VolGQDs/VolPP of 40 %, 66 %, and 400 %, are defined as PD2, PD3, and PD4, respectively. As the VolGQDs/VolPP increased, the dark current of the devices increased (Fig. 6
                     a), while the photocurrent decreased under reverse bias voltage conditions (Fig. 6b). Under 256 nm illumination with an optical power of 8.6 μW, the increase in VolGQDs/VolPP led to a decline in PDCR (Fig. 6c) and responsivity (Fig. 6d). Additionally, PD4 with the largest VolGQDs/VolPP exhibits the smallest SBUV–Vis rejection ratio (R256 nm/R425 nm
                     ) and the smallest D* (Fig. 6e and Fig. 6f). This may be due to the fact that GQDs are highly concentrated in PP@GQDs layer, which reduces the conductivity of the conductive layer. Thus, an increase in dark current, a decrease in photocurrent (responsivity), a decrease in PDCR, and a decrease in D*, these changes are found in PD4. This viewpoint is also supported by the I-V curves of the PP@GQDs layer with various VolGQDs/VolPP (Fig. S6 in Supplemental Information).

In short, a PP@GQDs/Lu0.39In0.61O/GaN SBUV photodetector with high photoresponsivity has been successfully fabricated by adopting PP@GQDs conductive polymer as both a transparent conductive window layer and a defect passivation layer. The device has achieved a responsivity (R256 nm
                     ) of 71.5 mA/W, a high detectivity (D*) of 8.8 × 1011 Jones, and a significant SBUV–Vis rejection ratio (R256 nm/425 nm
                     ) of 1.9 × 103 under 0 V bias and 8.6 μW SBUV illumination. Additionally, it exhibited an EQE of nearly 34.6 %, which is one order of magnitude higher than that of most amorphous SBUV photovoltaic devices. All of these are attributed to the embedded GQDs in PEDOT:PSS, which not only increase the barrier height of the electrode/Lu0.39In0.61O interface, but also decrease the interface states density. Furthermore, it is concluded that an appropriate concentration of GQDs is crucial for balancing carrier separation efficiency and transport efficiency. The proposed interface engineering of modulating surface defects of the amorphous compound and the Schottky barrier of the amorphous/electrode interface will provide new guidance for the fabrication of high responsivity and high EQE SBUV photovoltaic devices based on amorphous compound in the future.
